@harryh [Given the dynamics I propose here, if relevant] why do you feel that Wikipedia is successful as a counterexample?
(Corollary: the better your anti-spam enforcement, the worse your ad products can be.)
Thus, ad products and spam lie on the same continuum, so UGC sites must provide an ad product with higher ROI than spamming.
The ad program must only allow ads which are not destructive to the site's content and UX (whereas spam does not care).
Sites without an ad program have a very low threshold of ROI to meet (zero) for spam to be worthwhile.
The ROI of any site-sanctioned ad product must exceed the "spam" ROI or the advertisers will prefer to spam, overrunning the site.
Ads/spam reach an ROI equilibrium defined by cost to run the ad multiplied by probability of being banned by anti-spam system.
#3 is inevitable if #1 does not exist because not all users are as scrupulous as site owners, and anti-spam enforcement is never 100%.
3) advertisers independently contact regular users and pay them to broadcast their message for them ("spam").
2) advertisers join the site as user accounts, or
1) the site allows ads by creating an ad program, or
But any site that gains enough reach to be relevant becomes valuable to advertisers. On UGC sites, one of the following things then happens:
A sole-publisher content site can decide unilaterally never to accept advertising, and pursue other revenue sources instead.
Theory: all user-generated content sites inevitably have ads on them.
